: NEXT Gomme

## Gomme: Error messages

Parser combinator libraries seemed to fit the requirement of maintainability best.
So I ended up forking a Go parser combinator library and adding all the missing features.

In this talk you will see how I had to do research normally done for a PhD thesis
and had to completely change how the parser works multiple times.
Furthermore you will learn what makes error recovery easier and what makes it harder.
And how you can implement it under the hardest possible conditions (that of a parser combinator library).

After one year of sweat, sleepless nights and tears the project finally has all the desired features.
So now it is the ultimate Go parser combinator library for me.
And of course you will learn in the talk how you can easily write a great parser with it
(without sweat, sleepless nights or tears).


## The Last Tough Decision

<table>
<thead><tr> <th>Topics</th> <th>1 subparser</th> <th>N subparsers</th> </tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr> <th>children</th> <td>trivial</td> <td>lots of parsers but doable; prentheses???</td> </tr>
<tr> <th># of children</th> <td>always 3</td> <td>N * M + 2 + parentheses</td> </tr>
<tr> <th>who failed?</th> <td>remember err + op</td> <td>trivial: ID</td> </tr>
<tr> <th>who recovered?</th> <td>remember err + op</td> <td>done automatically</td> </tr>
<tr> <th>parents?</th> <td>remember err + ops + levels</td> <td>remember in result</td> </tr>
<tr> <th>parsers</th> <td>just 2 to the outside</td> <td>facade parsers for ops + parentheses</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

